Vladimir Putin and the Risk of a Third World War
San Francisco – February 24, The Russian invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of a third world war that could possibly destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping had a long meeting on February 4, which coincided with the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the opening of the Beijing Winter Olympics.
After the meeting, the two leaders released a 5,000-word document announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is stronger than any treaty and definitely requires thorough prior negotiations.
I am shocked that Xi seems to have entrusted Putin to invade and wage war in Ukraine.
He thinks that confirming himself as China's lifetime ruler in the second half of the year is just a formality, and he is full of confidence in this.
After concentrating all power in his own hands, Xi carefully plotted a scheme to upgrade himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After receiving Xi's support, Putin began to fulfill his lifelong dream in a barbaric and unbelievable way.
At the age of over 70, Putin feels that if he wants to leave a bold stroke in Russian history, then it's now, or he will never be able to.
But he has a distorted view of Russia's influence in the world.
He seems to think that the Russian people need a tsar they can blindly follow.
This system is in stark contrast to a democratic society, and this vision has distorted the "soul" of the Russians to an emotional and overly sentimental degree.
As a child, I had many encounters with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them for something, they will share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I called my political philanthropic career.
Originally, I set up a foundation in my native Hungary, and then actively participated in activities that led to the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, this dissolution had already begun.
I also set up a foundation in Russia, and later in each of the republics that emerged independently.
In Ukraine, I even set up a foundation before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (I closed this foundation in 1989, and shortly after the Tiananmen Square Massacre broke out).
I personally don't know Putin, but I closely followed his rise and fully understand his cold-blooded character.
He leveled the Chechen capital Grozny to the ground; now he is threatening to do the same to the Ukrainian capital Kyiv.
Putin was once a clever KGB agent, but he has seemed to change lately.
He seems to have lost touch with reality because he has formed a fixed idea.
There is no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He thought that the Ukrainians who speak Russian would open their arms to the Russian soldiers, but in fact, they are no different from the Ukrainian-speaking civilians.
Confronting the seemingly one-sided possibility, the Ukrainian civilians still carried out an incredible heroic resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article stating that the Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and the Ukrainians have been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
Because Kyiv is the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, his first point is not entirely without historical basis.
But in the 2nd part of the content, Putin was misled.
He should have known the facts more clearly.
Many Ukrainians bravely fought in the Euromaidan protests in 2014.
The 2014 event made him very angry.
However, when he received the order to attack his Ukrainian brothers, the Russian army performed poorly.
The defense ministry granting them the award at the same time also played an important role in their poor performance.
But Putin not only didn't blame himself, but instead seemed to have gone mad.
He had decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him, and his actions seemed to be without any constraints.
He threw the entire Russian military into battle and disregarded all rules of engagement, especially indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals were bombed, and the power grid that supplies electricity to the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (which has currently been occupied by Russian troops) was also destroyed.
In the besieged Mariupol, as many as 400,000 people have gone without water and food for a week.
Russia may lose this war.
The US and EU are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine at the same time as they are trying to buy Russian MIG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
This could change the entire situation.
Either way, Putin has made miracles in strengthening European resolve and unity.
With this, Xi seems to have realized that Putin has gone off track.
On March 8, after China's Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that the friendship between China and Russia is still "solid as a rock", Xi telephoned French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to express his support for their peacekeeping activities.
To avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to keep the maximum restraint in the war.
It is still impossible to determine whether Putin will yield to Xi's will.
We can only hope that, before Putin and Xi destroy our civilization, they will be kicked off the stage.
